The Mean

1 What does the mean mean?

Lets say youre interested in how dogs from Florida and Georgia differ by weight.

1.0.1 Sampling

Since we cant take the weight of EVERY dog in these these two states, we have to rely on taking the weights of randomly selected groups of dogs. Lets weigh 100 different dogs in each state.

1.0.2 Taking the mean

Itd be really hard to eyeball 100 different numbers and be able to say something about dogs in Georgia or Florida. We need to summarize these weights into a single number per group that will be meaningful the mean!

The mean is the average. It is the sum of all of the weights divided by the number of dogs for the group. All dogs will be labeled x, and the numerical subscript indicates the dogs number in the group.

Well use \(\color{blue}{\bar{x}}\) (read x-bar) to represent the mean of each sample, calculated with the following equation:

\[\begin{equation} \tag{1.1} \Large \color{blue}{\bar{x}} = \frac{x_1 + x_2 + ... + x_n}{n} \end{equation}\]

To make this more efficient, instead of writing \({x_1 + x_2 + ... + x_n}\), we can use the sigma symbol to represent summation of all the observations.

\[\begin{equation} \tag{1.2} \Large \color{blue}{\bar{x}} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_i}{n} \end{equation}\]
This might look intimidating, but it means the same thing as (1.1). Lets break the symbols apart a bit. The sigma \(\sum{}\) means add up. What are we adding up? All the observations x. The i=1 means that we start with the first x on our list. The character on top of the sigma is the last observation we include in our summation. In this case its nbecause were adding all n = 100 observations in each group of dogs. In both equations, we still divide by the total number of observations in each group we have: n.

1.0.3 Code it up

Using (1.2), its easy to translate this into code in R.

1.0.4 Create your own function

Now its your turn to write your own function. Call it my_mean and have it calculate the mean of any given vector. Do this in RStudio on your local computer.

1.0.5 Things to think about

How reliably does the sample mean represent the population mean? See the Law of Large Numbers.
